==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Haven
<hw>Ha"ven</hw> <pr>(h⟦amac⟧"v'n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>h⟦ae⟧fene</ets>; akin to D. & LG. <ets>haven</ets>, G.
<ets>hafen</ets>, MHG. <ets>habe</ets>, Dan. <ets>havn</ets>, Icel.
<ets>h⟦oum⟧fn</ets>, Sw. <ets>hamn</ets>; akin to E. <ets>have</ets>,
and hence orig., a holder; or to <ets>heave</ets> (see <er>Heave</er>);
or akin to AS. <ets>h⟦ae⟧f</ets> sea, Icel. & Sw. <ets>haf</ets>, Dan.
<ets>hav</ets>, which is perh. akin to E. <ets>heave</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A bay, recess, or inlet of the sea, or the mouth of a
river, which affords anchorage and shelter for shipping; a harbor; a
port.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What shipping and what lading 's in our <qex>haven</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their <qex>haven</qex> under the hill.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A place of safety; a shelter; an asylum.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>haven</qex>, or the rock of love.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Haven</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Haven
<hw>Ha"ven</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To shelter, as in a haven.</def>
<rj><au>Keats.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Havenage</ent>⟦br⟧
